---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="About - LocalResizer" description="Learn about LocalResizer, a browser-based static image tool focused on privacy and practical image tasks.">
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-16 prose prose-slate">
    <h1>About LocalResizer</h1>
    <p>LocalResizer is a browser-based tool for static image resizing and compression. The current site focuses on practical JPEG, PNG, and WebP tasks that can be completed entirely on your device.</p>
    <h2>Why This Site Exists</h2>
    <p>LocalResizer exists for a simple reason: many image tasks should not require uploading files to a remote server just to hit a size limit or match a standard canvas. The site is designed around privacy-first local processing for common static-image constraints, especially upload-size limits and fixed social-media artwork sizes.</p>
    <h2>How It Works</h2>
    <p>The site uses browser-native canvas processing so your image stays in the tab where you opened the tool. There is no server upload step for the current image workflow.</p>
    <h2>How We Measure the Site</h2>
    <p>We use privacy-friendly analytics to understand broad page usage and discoverability, but those analytics do not include the images you process. The analytics help us improve navigation and content quality without changing the local-processing promise.</p>
    <h2>Who the Current Release Is For</h2>
    <p>The current public release is built for people who need quick, practical static-image help: creators preparing YouTube assets, site owners reducing upload weight, and anyone trying to meet a size limit without installing desktop software for a one-off task.</p>
    <h2>What the Site Covers Right Now</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>General homepage tool</strong> for quick file-size compression or dimension-based resizing</li>
      <li><strong>Target-size pages</strong> such as 50 KB, 100 KB, 200 KB, and 2 MB workflows</li>
      <li><strong>Exact canvas pages</strong> for current YouTube banner and thumbnail dimensions</li>
      <li><strong>Guide pages</strong> that group the current live compression, resize-by-size, and YouTube image workflows</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>How We Publish Pages</h2>
    <p>We try to publish only pages that match a real live workflow in the site. That means the public copy, guide pages, and trust pages are meant to describe what the current release can actually do today, not a future roadmap. When a workflow is not ready for public use, we would rather keep it out of scope than overclaim.</p>
    <h2>Supported Files</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>JPEG</strong> for photos and lighter lossy compression</li>
      <li><strong>PNG</strong> for graphics and transparent images</li>
      <li><strong>WebP</strong> for modern static image compression</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>What Each Live Page Type Means</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Compress pages</strong> aim for a target file size locally, with JPEG and WebP using quality search and PNG staying in PNG format.</li>
      <li><strong>Resize-to-size pages</strong> reduce image dimensions toward a target file-size budget while keeping the original aspect ratio.</li>
      <li><strong>Exact canvas pages</strong> create a fixed output size for current YouTube artwork and keep the whole image visible inside that canvas.</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>Current Public Limits</h2>
    <p>The public scope is limited to static image workflows for JPEG, PNG, and WebP files. Animated formats, video tools, and automatic crop workflows are not part of the current release.</p>
    <h2>Maintenance and Support</h2>
    <p>LocalResizer is still in an early stage, so the site is intentionally focused. We review support requests, bug reports, and workflow gaps to decide what gets improved next. Questions, bug reports, and partnership inquiries can be sent to <a href="mailto:support@localresizer.com">support@localresizer.com</a>.</p>
    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>Questions or feedback? Reach us at <a href="/contact">the contact page</a>.</p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
